'''Hippobotus''' ({{IPAc-en|h|ᵻ|ˈ|p|ɒ|b|ə|t|ə|s}}; {{lang-grc|Ἱππόβοτος}}; {{floruit}} {{circa}} 200 BC) was a Greek [[historian]] of philosophers and philosophical schools. His writings are frequently quoted by [[Diogenes Laërtius]].<ref>Diogenes Laërtius, i. 19, 42; ii. 88; v. 90; vi. 85, 102; vii. 25, 38; viii. 43, 51, 72; ix. 5, 40, 115</ref> He wrote ''On the Sects'' ({{lang-el|Περὶ Αἱρέσεων}})<ref>Diogenes Laërtius, i. 19, ii. 88</ref> and a ''Register of Philosophers'' ({{lang-el|Τῶν Φιλοσόφων Ἀναγραφή}}).<ref>Diogenes Laërtius, i. 42</ref> He treated philosophers as early as the [[Seven Sages of Greece|Seven Sages]] and [[Pythagoras]], and as late as [[Crates of Thebes|Crates]], [[Menedemus the Cynic|Menedemus]], and [[Zeno of Citium|Zeno]], hence it is inferred that he wrote in the 3rd or 2nd century BC. His work included lists of pupils of Zeno<ref>Diogenes Laërtius, vii. 38</ref> and [[Timon of Phlius|Timon]].<ref>Diogenes Laërtius, ix. 115</ref> Diogenes Laërtius relates that Hippobotus refused to put the [[Cynicism (philosophy)|Cynic]], [[Eleatic]] and Dialectical schools into his ''On Sects''.<ref>Diogenes Laërtius, i. 19</ref>
==Notes== {{reflist}}
[[Category:3rd-century BC historians]] [[Category:Ancient Greek biographers]] [[Category:Hellenistic-era historians]]

[[File:Hopewell Culture Pot.jpg|thumb|Hopewell pot with bird design at [[Hopewell Culture National Historical Park]] museum]] [[File:Hopewell jar, Mound City.jpg|thumb|Hopewell jar from Hopewell Culture National Historical Park. Dated to ca. 1-350 CE, it may have been imported from the southern Appalachian or Gulf Coastal Plain area.]] '''Hopewell pottery''' is the ceramic tradition of the various local cultures involved in the [[Hopewell tradition]] (ca. 200 BCE to 400 CE)<ref>[http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/dictionary/index.asp "Hopewell (Archaeology)."] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820033016/http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/dictionary/index.asp |date=2012-08-20 }} ''Wisconsin Historical Society.'' (retrieved 19 July 2010)</ref> and are found as [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]] in [[archeological site]]s in the American Midwest and Southeast. The Hopewell were located around the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]] and [[Illinois River]]s during the [[Woodland period|Middle Woodland Period]], and the Hopewell Interaction Sphere spanned from the [[Gulf of Mexico]] to [[Ontario]], Canada.<ref>Berlo and Phillips, 77</ref>
==Uses== This pottery was used in a variety of ways: from storage and cooking to holding offerings during burial ceremonies. Ceremonial pottery was noticeably more delicate and elaborate than pottery for domestic use.<ref name=s65>Seeman, 65</ref>
==Techniques== Although there are many techniques and methods of pottery production, the method most likely used in the Hopewell culture was the coiled method. After making the initial form of the vessel a paddle and anvil would then be used to further shape and smooth the pot. The final two steps are decoration and firing.
Before firing, Hopewell pottery was often incised, stamped, or zone-stamped, in which different "zones" of the pot were delineating by incised, then stamped, leaving the surrounding areas smooth for contrast.<ref>Seeman, 64</ref> "Hopewell ware" is characterized by [[crosshatching]], bands with cambered rims, and highly stylized bird motifs.<ref name=s65/>
==See also== * [[Ceramics of indigenous peoples of the Americas]] * [[Fort Ancient culture pottery]] * [[Mississippian culture pottery]] * [[Plaquemine culture pottery]] * [[Visual arts by indigenous peoples of the Americas]]
