{{Infobox Politician | name = Ronald van Raak | image = Ronald van Raak portret 3.jpg | imagesize = | office = [[House of Representatives of the Netherlands|Member of the House of Representatives of the Netherlands]] | term_start = 30 November 2006 | term_end = | office1 = [[Senate of the Netherlands|Member of the Senate]] | term_start1 = 10 June 2003 | term_end1 = 28 November 2006 | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1969|10|30|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Hilvarenbeek]], [[Netherlands]] | birthname = Antonius Adrianus Gerardus Maria van Raak | nationality = [[Netherlands|Dutch]] | party = [[Socialist Party (Netherlands)|Socialist Party]] (Socialistische Partij - SP) | relations = Married | residence = [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands | alma_mater = [[Erasmus University Rotterdam]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]] - [[Social history]], MA - [[Philosophy]])<br/ >[[University of Amsterdam]] ([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] - [[Humanities]]) | occupation = Politician, non-fiction writer, academic | religion = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] <ref>{{nl}} [http://www.perdefinitie.nl/?do=profile&mid=112 Perdefinitie.nl biography]</ref> | signature = | website = {{nl}} [http://www.sp.nl/partij/gekozen/ronaldvanraak.stm Socialist Party website] }}
'''Antonius Adrianus Gerardus Maria (Ronald) van Raak''' (born 30 October 1969 in [[Hilvarenbeek]]) is a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[politician]], [[non-fiction]] writer and former [[academic]]. As a member of the [[Socialist Party (Netherlands)|Socialist Party]] (Socialistische Partij) he has been an [[House of Representatives of the Netherlands|MP]] since 30 November 2006. He focuses on matters of [[home affairs]], [[Kingdom of the Netherlands|Kingdom relations]], the [[Dutch Royal House]] and general affairs. From 2003 to 2006 he was a [[Senate of the Netherlands|Senator]].
== Biography == Van Raak is of a [[working class|working-class]] background; his father was a [[truck driver]]. He grew up in his native village and attended secondary education in [[Tilburg]]. Afterwards he studied both [[social history]] and [[philosophy]] at [[Erasmus University Rotterdam]] and got [[promotion (academic)|promoted]] in [[humanities]] at the [[University of Amsterdam]].
On 1 April 2000 he joined the Socialist Party and started to work at SP's [[think tank]]. Three years later he became director.
In 2003 he was elected into the [[Senate of the Netherlands|Dutch Senate]] and was a member from 10 June that year till 28 November 2006. In November 2006 he was elected into the [[House of Representatives of the Netherlands|Dutch House of Representatives]]. The same month he changed positions, instead of being director he became SP's think tank chairman.
From 2001 to 2005 he also taught history at the University of Amsterdam.
